<header class="header">
  <h1>Short-Season Sweet Corn Varieties</h1>
  <p class="tagline">
    Choose sweet corn that can reach eating stage before cool weather slows the crop down.
  </p>
  <p class="lede">
    <strong>Short-season sweet corn varieties mature earlier and give gardeners in cooler climates a better chance of harvesting full ears before the season ends.</strong>
  </p>
</header>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Quick Answer</h2>
  <p>
    For short growing seasons, choose early sweet corn varieties and plant after soil has warmed. Corn needs both frost-free time and steady heat, so late or cold planting can erase the advantage of an early variety.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Safest choices:</strong> early-maturing sweet corn varieties</li>
    <li><strong>Higher risk:</strong> long-season main-crop corn in cool climates</li>
    <li><strong>Main challenge:</strong> enough heat for strong growth and full ears</li>
    <li><strong>Best strategy:</strong> choose an early variety and plant in blocks for pollination</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>What Makes Sweet Corn Short-Season Friendly?</h2>
  <p>
    Sweet corn is sensitive to cold soil and slow starts. A short-season variety helps, but the crop still needs warm enough conditions to grow quickly and pollinate well.
  </p>
  <p>
    Early corn may produce smaller plants or ears than some long-season types, but it gives you more harvest margin when the season is limited.
  </p>
  <ul class="tight">
    <li><strong>Early maturity:</strong> gives more room before fall cold.</li>
    <li><strong>Strong seedling vigor:</strong> helpful when spring warms slowly.</li>
    <li><strong>Good pollination setup:</strong> corn should be planted in blocks, not single long rows.</li>
    <li><strong>Realistic harvest goal:</strong> earlier corn is often safer than maximum ear size.</li>
  </ul>
</section>

