<section class="card">
  <h2>Early Corn Still Needs Warm Soil</h2>
  <p>
    Planting sweet corn too early can backfire. Cold soil slows germination and weakens the stand, which can delay the crop even if the variety is early.
  </p>
  <p>
    In short seasons, the goal is not simply the earliest possible planting date. The goal is the earliest safe planting date that gives the corn warm enough conditions to grow strongly.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Common Mistakes When Choosing Short-Season Sweet Corn</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Planting in cold soil:</strong> poor germination can ruin the stand.</li>
    <li><strong>Choosing only long-season favorites:</strong> they may not finish in cool areas.</li>
    <li><strong>Planting a single row:</strong> poor pollination leads to poorly filled ears.</li>
    <li><strong>Ignoring heat accumulation:</strong> corn needs warm growing weather, not just frost-free days.</li>
    <li><strong>Starting too late:</strong> late planting can push harvest into cool fall weather.</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Best Strategy for Short Seasons</h2>
  <p>
    Choose an early sweet corn variety, wait for suitable soil warmth, and plant in a block for pollination. In very short seasons, early varieties are usually safer than longer-season corn with larger plants or later ears.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Plan Around Your Local Season</h2>
  <p>
    Sweet corn needs enough warm days after planting to reach eating stage. Check your frost window, spring soil timing, and seasonal heat before choosing a variety.
